data.content:
Yes! MSTest has `[DataRow]` for simple inline cases, which is cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**Why it's better:**
- No `object[]` boxing — parameters are strongly typed
- Less boilerplate (no separate property)
- Each case shows as a distinct test row in the runner

**When to keep `DynamicData`:** if your test data is complex (custom objects, computed values, or too many parameters). In that case, use tuples or a typed record instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
    new (string Input, bool Expected)[]
    {
        ("valid@email.com", true),
        ("invalid", false),
    }.Select(t => new object[] { t.Input, t.Expected });
```

For your simple scenario, `[DataRow]` is the clear winner.
